<paragraph id="341836CCB561DB7C6CD7B4D0FE99F8ED" blockId="3.[151,640,1665,1725]" box="[151,350,1700,1725]" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">
(
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B561DB7C6CDFB4D0FEC4F8EC" box="[159,259,1700,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1766,1789]" captionTargetBox="[232,1349,195,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[232,1350,195,1734]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in dorsal and ventral views. 1 – 2 M. gracielae sp. nov., male holotype. 3 – 4 M. monostigma monostigma, male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil. 5 – 8 M. nepticula stigmosa, 5 – 6 male; 7 – 8 female. 9 – 12 M. eupteryx stat. rest., 9 – 10 male from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 11 – 12 female. 13 – 14 M. nola, male from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil. 15 – 20 M. paraena, 15 – 16 male from Cáceres, Mato Grosso, Brazil; 17 – 18 male; 19 – 20 female. 21 – 28 M. epaphus (23 – 28 upper side left, underside right), 21 – 22 M. epaphus pyrrha, male; 23 female from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil; 24 female from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 25 M. epaphus epaphus, male from Belém, Pará, Brazil; 26 M. epaphus pyrrha, male from São Paulo de Olivença, Amazonas, Brazil; 27 – 28, M. epaphus pyrrha, males from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil. 29 – 32 M. leucophrys, 29 – 30 male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil; 31 – 32 female. Scale bar 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256291/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">Figs 5–8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B561DB7C6D4FB4D0FEEAF8EC" box="[271,301,1700,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 33 – 40" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1900,1923]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,193,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1880]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 33 – 40. Male genitalia of Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in lateral view. 33 M. gracielae sp. nov., holotype. 34 M. monostigma monostigma. 35 M. nepticula stigmosa. 36 M. eupteryx stat. rest. from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil (DZ 36.494). 37 M. nola from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil (DZ 36.794). 38 M. paraena. 39 M. epaphus pyrrha. 40 M. leucophrys. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/161477/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">35</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B561DB7C6D79B4D0FE91F8ED" box="[313,342,1700,1724]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 45" captionStartId="6.[151,264,913,936]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,891]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,892]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 45. Female genitalia of Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in ventral view. 41, M. nepticula stigmosa. 42, M. eupteryx stat. rest. 43, M. paraena. 44, M. epaphus pyrrha from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil (DZ 36.504). 45, M. leucophrys. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/161478/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">41</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7CBD6547B561DB7C6CD7B498FE10F9E9" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" type="description">
<paragraph id="341836CCB561DB7C6CD7B498FBB8F978" blockId="3.[151,1436,1772,1977]" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">Eight males and two females of this taxon were collected on the hilltop of the PNSD in 2014. All specimens were observed from mid-afternoon to sunset, flying from two to four meters above the ground.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="341836CCB561DB7C6C87B540FE10F9E9" blockId="3.[151,1436,1772,1977]" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">
The phenotype of the specimens found at the PNSD is similar to the type specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB561DB7C68E1B541FE42F920" authority="Warren et al. 2016" authorityName="Warren et al." authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="nepticula" subSpecies="stigmosa">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB561DB7C68E1B541FA5CF91D" box="[1185,1435,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">M. nepticula stigmosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB561DB7C6CDEB52CFEB9F920" author="Warren" box="[158,382,1880,1905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" refString="Warren, A. D., Davis, K. J., Stangeland, E. M., Pelham, J. P. &amp; Grishin, N. V. (2016) Illustrated lists of American butterflies (North and South America). Available from: http: // butterfliesofamerica. com / L / Neotropical. htm (accessed 23 May 2016)" type="journal article" year="2016">
Warren 
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB561DB7C6CBCB52DFEF0F920" box="[252,311,1880,1905]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB561DB7C6ED5B52DFC53F921" box="[661,916,1880,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="nepticula" subSpecies="stigmosa">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB561DB7C6ED5B52DFC53F921" box="[661,916,1880,1905]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">M. nepticula stigmosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB561DB7C6872B52DFA86F920" authority="Bates, 1868" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1868" box="[1074,1345,1880,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB561DB7C6872B52DFB68F920" box="[1074,1199,1880,1905]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">M. simplex</emphasis>
Bates, 1868
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB561DB7C693DB52DFDC3F9C5" authority="Hall &amp; Lamas, 2007" authorityName="Hall &amp; Lamas" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucogyna">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB561DB7C693DB52DFECDF9C4" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="466">M. leucogyna</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB561DB7C6D54B508FDC3F9C5" author="Hall" box="[276,516,1916,1941]" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" refString="Hall, J. P. W. &amp; Lamas, G. (2007) Four new symmachiine taxa from the eastern Andes of Peru and Ecuador (Lepidoptera: Riodinidae). Zootaxa, 1533, 41 - 52." type="journal article" year="2007">Hall &amp; Lamas, 2007</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; these three species probably are closely related, belonging to the same species group (
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB561DB7C6CA7B5D4FE0CF9E9" author="Hall" box="[231,459,1952,1977]" pageId="3" pageNumber="466" refString="Hall, J. P. W. &amp; Lamas, G. (2007) Four new symmachiine taxa from the eastern Andes of Peru and Ecuador (Lepidoptera: Riodinidae). Zootaxa, 1533, 41 - 52." type="journal article" year="2007">Hall &amp; Lamas 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
